                "name": "Bj\u00f6rn Drescher",
                "href": "/profile/Bj\u00f6rn-Drescher"
            },
            "answer_text": "Napoleon. The early 19th century was characterized primarily by the various coalition wars against France, and for quite a while the German states (with the exception of Austria) were little more than french puppet states. That made it pretty clear to anyone at the time that a loose federation of small states was in no shape to resist any foreign invader anymore, and any foreign allies were unreliable at best. Only a unified Germany with a shared purpose would be able to prevent that from happening again. ",
